<h1>Use of the Volitional</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<p>
<dl>
<dt> (A) </dt> <dd>@Vyou{{}} @HI{{to @KJ{{think}}tteimasu.}} </dd>
<dt> (B) </dt> <dd>@Vyou{{}} @HI{{to @KJ{{think}}imasu.}} </dd>
</dl>
</p>

<h2> Definition </h2>

Volitional verbs are used in plain style ssentence in place of the @HI{{mashou}} form.
of a transitive verb becomes @HI{{ga}} when the verb is in the volitional form.
<p></p>

The sentence pattern (A) above can be used to express what the speaker is thinking of doing.
Sentence pattern (B) expresses a similar meaning but the former implies that the decision
was made some time ago.
<p></p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{chotto @KJ{{rest}}manai?}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{un, @KJ{{rest}}<strong>mou</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: Shall we rest?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: yes, let's.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{week}}@KJ{{end}}ha @KJ{{sea}}ni @KJ{{going}}kou<strong>to @KJ{{think}}tteimasu</strong>.}}
      @KJ{{interchange}}@HI{{eraremasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'm thinking of going to the beach at the weekend.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

